06938nam a22010335i 9783110581416DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105814167 a10.1515/97831105814162doi  a(DE-B1597)490172  a(OCoLC)1046607362  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0060902bisacsh04aThe Bible, Qumran, and the Samaritans /ced. by Magnar Kartveit, Gary N. Knoppers. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudia Samaritana ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tQumran, Mount Gerizim, and the Books of Moses -- tOvercoming the Sub-Deuteronomism and Sub-Chronicism of Historiography in Biblical Studies: The Case of the Samaritans¹ -- tTextual Harmonization in the Five Books of the Torah: A Summary -- tSamaritan Studies – Recent Research Results -- tCult Centralization and the Publication of the Torah Between Jerusalem and Samaria -- tCompeting Attitudes toward Samaria in Chronicles and Second Zechariah -- tThe Composition of Ezra-Nehemiah as a Testimony for the Competition Between the Temples in Jerusalem and on Mt. Gerizim in the Early Years of the Seleucid Rule over Judah* -- tEthnic Fiction and Identity-Formation: A New Explanation for the Background of the Question of Intermarriage in Ezra-Nehemiah¹ -- tAn Update of Moses Gaster’s “Chain of Samaritan High Priests” -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Ancient Texts -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiscoveries on Mount Gerizim and in Qumran demonstrate that the final editing of the Hebrew Bible coincides with the emergence of the Samaritans as one of the different types of Judaisms from the last centuries BCE. This book discusses this new scholarly situation. Scholars working with the Bible, especially the Pentateuch, and experts on the Samaritans approach the topic from the vantage point of their respective fields of expertise. Earlier, scholars who worked with Old Testament/Hebrew Bible studies mostly could leave the Samaritan material to experts in that area of research, and scholars studying the Samaritan material needed only sporadically to engage in Biblical studies. This is no longer the case: the pre-Samaritan texts from Qumran and the results from the excavations on Mount Gerizim have created an area of study common to the previously separated fields of research. Scholars coming from different directions meet in this new area, and realize that they work on the same questions and with much common material.This volume presents the current state of scholarship in this area and the effects these recent discoveries have for an understanding of this important epoch in the development of the Bible.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aBibel. 4aPentateuch. 4aQumran. 4aSamaritaner. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aBible.  aPentateuch.  aQumran.  aSamaritans.1 aGonzalez, Hervé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeckl, Raik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHensel, Benedikt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKartveit, Magnar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKartveit, Magnar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnoppers, Gary N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoppers, Gary N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNihan, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula